<p>Ratios appear in recipes, investment portfolios, map scales, salary packages, and mathematical problems at every level of education. This guide makes ratio calculation simple and intuitive — with practical examples, simplification methods, and common applications from daily Indian life.</p>

<h2>What is a Ratio?</h2>
<p>A ratio is a comparison of two or more quantities. It tells you how many times one value is contained in another, or the relative size of two quantities. Ratios can be written as 3:4, 3 to 4, or 3/4, and all three notations mean the same thing. Understanding ratios is fundamental to mixing materials, dividing profits, cooking, and analysing financial statements.</p>

<h2>How to Calculate and Express a Ratio</h2>
<div style="background:#f4f6f8;padding:20px;border-left:5px solid #4f46e5;margin:20px 0;border-radius:8px;">
    <strong>Ratio of A to B = A : B</strong><br>
    To simplify: Divide both by their GCD (Greatest Common Divisor)<br>
    <strong>Simplified Ratio = (A/GCD) : (B/GCD)</strong>
</div>

<h2>Step-by-Step: Simplifying a Ratio</h2>
<p>Simplify the ratio 48:72.</p>
<ol>
    <li>Find GCD of 48 and 72: Factors of 48 = {1,2,3,4,6,8,12,16,24,48}. Factors of 72 = {1,2,3,4,6,8,9,12,18,24,36,72}. GCD = 24.</li>
    <li>48 ÷ 24 = 2 | 72 ÷ 24 = 3</li>
    <li>Simplified Ratio = <strong>2:3</strong></li>
</ol>

<h2>Practical Ratio Calculations</h2>

<h3>Dividing a Value in a Given Ratio</h3>
<p>Brothers Rahul and Amit share profits in 3:5 ratio. Total profit: ₹1,20,000.</p>
<ol>
    <li>Total parts = 3 + 5 = 8</li>
    <li>Rahul's share = (3/8) × ₹1,20,000 = <strong>₹45,000</strong></li>
    <li>Amit's share = (5/8) × ₹1,20,000 = <strong>₹75,000</strong></li>
</ol>

<h3>Checking if Two Ratios are Equivalent</h3>
<p>Are 4:6 and 10:15 equivalent? Cross-multiply: 4×15 = 60 and 6×10 = 60. Since they're equal, <strong>yes, they are equivalent.</strong></p>

<h2>Real-World Applications of Ratios</h2>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Cooking:</strong> A recipe uses flour and sugar in a 3:1 ratio. For 600g flour, you need 200g sugar.</li>
    <li><strong>Unit Price Comparison:</strong> 500ml bottle: ₹80 vs 1L bottle: ₹145. Ratio: ₹0.160/ml vs ₹0.145/ml — the bigger bottle is cheaper.</li>
    <li><strong>Investment Allocation:</strong> Equity:Debt = 70:30 allocation. On ₹5,00,000 total: ₹3,50,000 in equity, ₹1,50,000 in debt.</li>
    <li><strong>Cement Mortar:</strong> Mixing cement and sand in 1:4 ratio for plaster work.</li>
    <li><strong>Map Scale:</strong> 1:50,000 scale map means 1 cm = 500 m in real life.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Not simplifying both numbers by the same GCD.</li>
    <li>Reversing the order — 3:5 is not the same as 5:3.</li>
    <li>Adding ratios incorrectly — 1:2 and 2:3 cannot be combined by adding numerators and denominators.</li>
    <li>Treating ratio as a fraction without recognising it represents parts of a whole.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="faq-section">
    <div class="faq-item"><h3>What is the difference between ratio and proportion?</h3><p>A ratio compares two quantities (3:4). A proportion states that two ratios are equal (3:4 = 6:8). Proportions are used to solve "if-then" scaling problems.</p></div>
    <div class="faq-item"><h3>Can ratios have decimals?</h3><p>Technically yes, but ratios are typically expressed in whole numbers for clarity. Multiply both parts by the appropriate power of 10 to eliminate decimals (e.g., 1.5:2.5 = 3:5).</p></div>
</div>

